  <h1>Forthglade vs Butternut Box for Puppies — Cold-Pressed vs Fresh</h1>

  <p class="meta" style="color: var(--color-text-light); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
    Last updated: June 2026 · 10 min read
  </p>

  <p>If you're feeding a new puppy in the UK and want to do it properly, two very different brands keep topping the lists: <strong>Forthglade</strong> and <strong>Butternut Box</strong>. Both are our top two picks in the <a href="/best-puppy-food-uk/">best puppy food guide</a> — but they solve the problem in opposite ways. Forthglade is <strong>cold-pressed dry food</strong> (with wet trays) you keep in the cupboard; Butternut Box is <strong>chilled fresh food</strong> delivered on subscription, portioned to your puppy's exact growth. This is the classic <strong>convenience-and-cost vs fresh-nutrition</strong> decision, set during the most important feeding months of a dog's life.</p>

  <p>The short version: <strong>Forthglade</strong> is the easiest, most affordable way to feed a puppy well — cupboard-stable, all-life-stage, around £0.70/day — and your pup never has to switch foods as it grows. <strong>Butternut Box</strong> scores higher on independent nutrition ratings, wins on palatability for fussy pups, and takes the guesswork out of portion control for growth — at roughly £2.40/day and the need for freezer space. This guide compares them head-to-head on nutrition, growth, storage, cost and convenience — informed by feeding our own dog, <strong>Milo, a 12-year-old Labrador/Lurcher rescue who's wheat-sensitive and has been on grain-free food his whole life</strong>, alongside published data and independent All About Dog Food (AADF) ratings.</p>

