  <h2>Nutrition & Ingredients</h2>

  <p>Both brands clear the puppy-nutrition bar comfortably, and both build on the same modern principles: named meat, grain-free, hypoallergenic and free from artificial additives. The difference is format and meat density.</p>

  <p><strong>Butternut Box</strong> leads on raw numbers. Its gently steam-cooked fresh meals are built on <strong>60% fresh meat</strong> with no grains, soya, sugar or salt, and rate <strong>93–94% on AADF</strong> — among the highest scores of any UK food. For a growing puppy, that high-quality, highly digestible protein is genuinely valuable, and the fresh format makes it very easy on developing skin and digestion.</p>

  <p><strong>Forthglade</strong> takes a different route. Its <strong>cold-pressed</strong> dry food is made at low temperatures that preserve more nutrients than standard high-heat extrusion, rated <strong>73–75% by AADF</strong>, and its <strong>wet trays score 77–88%</strong> — both excellent for cupboard-stored food and well above typical puppy kibble. Everything is grain-, gluten-free and hypoallergenic, with single-source named proteins that make it a clean choice if you suspect a specific intolerance. The Turkey Cold Pressed recipe even uses a smaller pellet ideal for tiny mouths and teething pups.</p>

  <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Butternut Box on absolute AADF nutrition and digestibility; Forthglade for a genuinely high-quality, hypoallergenic cupboard food that punches above its format.</p>

  <h2>Growth & Portion Control</h2>

  <p>This is the section that matters most for puppies, and it's where the two brands genuinely differ. Overfeeding a growing puppy — especially a <strong>large or giant breed</strong> — drives rapid growth that's linked to <strong>hip and elbow dysplasia</strong> and other developmental joint problems. Getting portions right isn't fussiness; it's protecting your dog's joints for life.</p>

  <p><strong>Butternut Box</strong> makes this almost automatic. Every plan is <strong>calculated to your puppy's current weight and growth target</strong>, delivered in pre-portioned pouches, and <strong>recalculated as your pup grows</strong>. You feed the pouch, and the maths is done for you — a real advantage for first-time owners or anyone nervous about overfeeding a fast-growing breed.</p>

  <p><strong>Forthglade</strong> reaches the same destination, but you drive. You weigh meals to the feeding guide and adjust the amount as your pup gains weight — slightly more attention, but completely manageable with kitchen scales and a feeding chart, and arguably it keeps you more closely tuned to your dog's condition.</p>

  <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Butternut Box for hands-off, growth-matched portion control; Forthglade if you're happy to weigh meals and stay hands-on.</p>

  <h2>Storage & Convenience</h2>

  <p>This is where Forthglade makes its case. It's <strong>shelf-stable cupboard food</strong> — no fridge, no freezer, no defrosting — which makes it far simpler for small kitchens, travel, holidays and dog-sitters. Scoop and serve.</p>

  <p><strong>Butternut Box</strong> is delivered <strong>frozen</strong>, so you need freezer space to store pouches and fridge space to defrost a few days at a time. It's a subscription rather than buy-as-you-go, which suits some owners and frustrates others. The convenience is in the delivery and the done-for-you portions; the inconvenience is the cold-storage footprint.</p>

  <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Forthglade for everyday convenience and zero cold-storage hassle; Butternut Box if you value doorstep delivery and don't mind making freezer room. If you love the idea of fresh but can't spare the freezer, a shelf-stable fresh food like <a href="/best-fresh-dog-food-uk/">Years</a> bridges the gap.</p>

  <h2>Cost</h2>

  <p>The gap is large and worth being honest about. <strong>Forthglade</strong> works out from around <strong>£0.70/day</strong> for a puppy, with the best per-unit price on a larger subscription. <strong>Butternut Box</strong> runs around <strong>£2.40/day for a small growing pup</strong> and noticeably more for larger breeds — so over a puppy's first year the difference adds up to hundreds of pounds.</p>

  <p>That premium isn't wasted — it buys higher AADF nutrition, top palatability and done-for-you portioning — but for a healthy, easy-to-feed puppy on a budget, Forthglade delivers most of the practical benefit for roughly a third of the cost. A popular middle path: feed Forthglade as the everyday base and use Butternut Box as a fresh topper or for fussy spells, getting fresh-food appeal without the full fresh-food bill.</p>

  <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Forthglade wins clearly on cost; Butternut Box justifies its premium for fussy pups and hands-off owners.</p>

  <h2>Which Should You Choose?</h2>

  <p>There's no single winner — it depends on your priorities and your puppy:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Choose Forthglade if:</strong> you want a convenient, cupboard-stored, all-life-stage food at around £0.70/day that your pup never has to switch off. Ideal for most healthy puppies, budget-conscious owners, and anyone who wants to avoid stressful diet changes as their dog grows.</li>
    <li><strong>Choose Butternut Box if:</strong> you want the highest AADF nutrition, effortless portion control matched to your puppy's growth, and maximum palatability for a fussy pup — and you're happy to pay around £2.40/day and make freezer space.</li>
    <li><strong>Feeding a large or giant breed?</strong> The portion-control advantage of Butternut Box (or careful weighing with Forthglade) matters most for you — controlled growth protects developing joints.</li>
    <li><strong>Want the best of both?</strong> Many owners run Forthglade as the everyday base and add Butternut Box as a fresh topper for fussy spells — fresh appeal, lower overall cost.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>For our own dog <strong>Milo (12)</strong>, who's been on grain-free, hypoallergenic food his whole life, the principle both brands follow — named single-source protein, no grains, gentle on digestion — is exactly what's kept his sensitivities in check from puppyhood to senior. For the wider field of puppy options, see our full <a href="/best-puppy-food-uk/">best puppy food UK guide</a>, and to understand the storage trade-off in the fresh category, see <a href="/years-vs-butternut-box/">Years vs Butternut Box</a>.</p>

  <h2>How to Switch</h2>

  <p>Whichever you choose, transition gradually over <strong>7-10 days</strong>, mixing increasing amounts of the new food into the old to protect a puppy's developing digestion. Puppies have smaller stomachs and faster metabolisms than adults, so feed little and often (typically 3-4 meals a day for young pups, reducing as they grow) and follow the brand's age-and-weight feeding guide closely. As always, if your puppy's appetite, weight, energy or toileting changes noticeably and doesn't settle, book a vet check.</p>

